ies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]] in 1976, but subsequently moved again and were renamed the [[New Jersey Devils]] in 1982.|group=note}}\n| 5\n| {{sort|1|[[Colorado Rapids|Rapids]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Phoenix metropolitan area|Phoenix]]\n| United States\n| 13\n| 4,661,537\n| 4\n| {{sort|1|[[Arizona Cardinals|Cardinals]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Arizona Diamondbacks|Diamondbacks]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Phoenix Suns|Suns]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Arizona Coyotes|Coyotes]]}}\n| 4\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Metro Detroit|Detroit]]\n| United States\n| 14\n| 4,297,617\n| 4\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Lions|Lions]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Tigers|Tigers]]}}{{refn|The [[Detroit Wolverines]] played in the [[National League]] from 1881 until the team disbanded in 1888.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Pistons|Pistons]]}}{{refn|The [[Detroit Falcons (basketball)|Detroit Falcons]] played in the [[1946-47 BAA season|inaugural season]] of what would become the NBA, but disbanded following that season.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Red Wings|Red Wings]]}}\n| 4\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Greater Toronto Area|Toronto]]\n| Canada\n| 10\n| 5,928,040\n| 3\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014 {{refn|While Toronto has not had an NFL franchise, the [[Buffalo Bills]] did host one of the team's regular season games each year and a number of pre-season games at the [[Rogers Centre]] from 2008 to 2013 as part of the [[Bills Toronto Series]].|group=note}}}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Blue Jays|Blue Jays]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]]}}{{refn|The [[Toronto Huskies]] played in the [[1946-47 BAA season|inaugural season]] of what would become the NBA, before dissolving.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]]}}\n| 5\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto FC]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Argonauts|Argonauts]]}}\n|-\n| [[Greater Houston|Houston]]\n| United States\n| 5\n| 6,772,470\n| 3\n| {{sort|1|[[Houston Texans|Texans]]}}{{refn|Houston hosted the [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]] from 1960 (where they played in the AFL until its merger with the NFL in 1970) through 1996 when the team moved to Tennessee\u2014initially being called the Tennessee Oilers in its first season in Memphis and its second season in Nashville until ultimately being renamed the [[Tennessee Titans]] upon the opening of the team's [[Nissan Stadium|current Nashville stadium]] in 1999.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Houston Astros|Astros]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Houston Rockets|Rockets]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| 4\n| {{sort|1|[[Houston Dynamo|Dynamo]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Atlanta metropolitan area|Atlanta]]\n| United States\n| 11\n| 5,789,700\n| 3\n| {{sort|1|[[Atlanta Falcons|Falcons]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Atlanta Braves|Braves]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Atlanta Hawks|Hawks]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|{{refn|The NHL expanded to Atlanta in 1972 with the [[Atlanta Flames]], but the team departed for [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]] in 1980 to become the [[Calgary Flames]]. In 1999 another expansion franchise, the [[Atlanta Thrashers]], was established, but this team moved to [[Winnipeg]] and became the [[Winnipeg Jets]] in 2011.|group=note}}}}\n| 4\n| {{sort|1|[[Atlanta United FC|United FC]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Tampa Bay Area]]\n| United States\n| 19\n| 3,032,171\n| 3\n| {{sort|1|[[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Buccaneers]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Tampa Bay Rays|Rays]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Tampa Bay Lightning|Lightning]]}}\n| 3\n| align=center|{{sort|0|{{refn|The [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]] was a charter franchise of MLS in 1996. However, the franchise folded in 2001.<ref name=\"MiamiTBMLS2002\" />|group=note}}}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Pittsburgh metropolitan area|Pittsburgh]]\n| United States\n| 28\n| 2,342,299\n| 3\n| {{sort|1|[[Pittsburgh Steelers|Steelers]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Pittsburgh Pirates|Pirates]]}}\n| align=center