}} [[British Columbia]]\n| ''28''\n| '''1'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Vancouver Canucks|Canucks]]}}\n| '''3'''\n| {{sort|1|[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC|Whitecaps FC]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[BC Lions|Lions]]}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Oregon]]\n| ''31''\n| '''1'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Portland Trail Blazers|Trail Blazers]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| '''2'''\n| {{sort|1|[[Portland Timbers|Timbers]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Utah]]\n| ''37''\n| '''1'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Utah Jazz|Jazz]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| '''2'''\n| {{sort|1|[[Real Salt Lake]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Manitoba]]\n| ''47''\n| '''1'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|  {{sort|1| [[Winnipeg Jets|Jets]]}}\n| '''2'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers|Blue Bombers]]}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Oklahoma]]\n| ''32''\n| '''1'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Oklahoma City Thunder|Thunder]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| '''1'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kansas]]\n| ''38''\n| '''0'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| '''1'''\n| {{sort|1|[[Sporting Kansas City]]{{#tag:ref|Sporting Kansas City play their home games at [[Children's Mercy Park]] in [[Kansas City, Kansas]].|name=MLSKC|group=note}}}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Saskatchewan]]\n| ''48''\n| '''0'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| '''1'''\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Saskatchewan Roughriders|Roughriders]]}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| '''34 states/{{shy}}provinces/{{shy}}districts'''\n| \n| '''123'''\n| '''32'''\n| '''30'''\n| '''30'''\n| '''31'''\n| '''158'''\n| '''26'''\n| '''9'''\n|}\n\n;Notes\n{{reflist|group=note|30em}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[U.S. cities with teams from four major league sports]]\n*[[List of auto racing tracks in the United States by city]]\n*[[List of professional golf tournaments in the United States by city]]\n*[[List of professional sports teams in the United States and Canada]]\n*[[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada]]\n*[[List of top level minor league sports teams in the United States by city]]\n*[[List of soccer clubs in the United States#By city|List of soccer clubs in the United States by city]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/ns/agalley/napsl/napsl1.html North American Pro Sports Teams] \u2013 Lists every league that has operated in Canada and/or the United States. Grouped by city.\n\n{{NFL}}\n{{MLB}}\n{{NBA}}\n{{NHL}}\n{{Major League Soccer}}\n{{CFL}}\n\n[[Category:Sports in the United States by city|Franchises]]\n[[Category:Sport in Canada by city]]\n[[Category:National Football League lists|Cities]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball lists|Cities]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association lists|Cities]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League lists|Cities]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer lists|Cities]]\n[[Category:Canadian Football League lists|Cities]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\nThis is a list of [[metropolitan area]]s in the United States and Canada categorized by the number of major [[professional sports]] franchises in their metropolitan areas.\n\n==Major professional sports leagues==\n{{Main|Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada}}\n\nThe '''major professional sports leagues''', or simply '''major leagues''', in the United States and Canada are the highest professional competitions of [[team sport]]s in the two countries. Although individual sports such as [[golf]], [[tennis]], and [[auto racing]] are also very popular, the term is usually limited to team sports.\n\nThe term \"major league\" was first used in 1921 in reference to [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB), the top level of professional American [[baseball]]. Today, the major northern North America professional team sports leagues are [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB), the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), the [[National Football League]] (NFL), and the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).<ref name=everson20090507>{{cite news|last=Everson|first=Darren|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124166336985294745|title=The Four Sports Commissioners Weigh In|page=D9|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=May 7, 2009|accessdate=March 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThese four leagues are also commonly referred to as the ''Big Four''. Each of these is the richest professional club competition in its sport worldwide. The best players can become [[cultural icon]]s in both countries and elsewhere in the world, because the leagues enjoy a significant place in [[popular culture]] in the [[Culture of the United States|U.S.]] and [[Canadian popular culture|Canada]]. The NFL has 32 teams, the NHL has 31, and MLB and the NBA each have 30. The most recent market to receive its first \"Big Four\" team is [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], which saw the NHL's [[Vegas Golden Knights]] make their debut for the 2017\u201318 season.\n\nBaseball, football, and hockey have had professional leagues for over 100 years; early leagues such as the [[National Association of Base Ball Players|National Association]], [[Ohio League]], and [[National Hockey Association]] formed the basis of the modern MLB, NFL and NHL respectively.  Basketball is a relatively new development; the NBA evolved from the [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]] and its splinter group the [[Basketball Association of America]], taking on its current form in 1949.\n\nOther notable leagues include [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) and the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL), both of which compare to the other four leagues in certain metrics but not in others. Every major league, including the CFL and MLS, draws 15,000 or more fans in attendance per game on average as of 2015. Therefore, this list includes a ranking by teams in the Big Four (B4), and a separate ranking also including teams in the CFL and MLS, called the Big Six (B6).\n\n==Metropolitan area==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2015}}\nThough teams are listed here by metropolitan area, the distribution and support of teams within an area can reveal regional fractures below that level, whether by neighborhood, rival cities within a [[media market]] or separate markets entirely. [[Baseball]] teams provide illustrations for several of these models. In New York City, the [[New York Yankees|Yankees]] are popularly dubbed the \"[[Bronx]] Bombers\" for their home borough and generally command the loyalties of fans from the Bronx, parts of [[Brooklyn]], [[Staten Island]], [[Manhattan]], [[Long Island]], parts of [[North Jersey]] and [[Westchester County, New York]], while the [[New York Mets|Mets]] play in [[Queens]] and draw support from Queens, Brooklyn and parts of Long Island, revealing a split by neighborhood. The [[San Francisco Giants]] and [[Oakland Athletics]] represent rival cities within the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]], a single media market. Though the [[Washington Nationals]] and [[Baltimore Orioles]] share a metro area, their cities anchor separate media markets and hold distinctly separate cultural identities. In Los Angeles, the [[Los Angeles Lakers|Lakers]] and [[Los Angeles Clippers|Clippers]] share an arena ([[Staples Center]]), and media coverage is split amongst different broadcasters in the metro area.\n\nWith the [[Vegas Golden Knights]], based in the [[Las Vegas Valley]], the 23rd largest market in North America, having joined the [[National Hockey League]] in 2017, the largest urban areas without a team in one of the big four leagues are the 32nd-ranked [[Greater Austin|Austin region]] and the 37th-ranked [[Hampton Roads|Virginia Beach-Norfolk region]]. The smallest metropolitan area to have a Big Four team is [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]] ([[Green Bay Packers]]), which is the 146th largest metropolitan area, though much of its fan base is drawn from [[Milwaukee]], which is 120 miles away and the 38th largest market. The smallest stand-alone metropolitan area to have a Big Four team is the 78th-largest market, [[Winnipeg]] ([[Winnipeg Jets]]), while the 54th-largest market, [[New Orleans \u2013 Metairie \u2013 Bogalusa combined statistical area|New Orleans]], is the smallest metropolitan area to have more than one Big Four team ([[New Orleans Pelicans]] and [[New Orleans Saints]]).\n\n[[Foxboro, Massachusetts]], population 16,685 as of the 2010 Census, is a small town which hosts two major-league teams (the [[New England Patriots]] and the [[New England Revolution]]). Foxboro is considered part of the [[Greater Boston|Boston metropolitan area]], even though it is slightly closer to [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. In a comparable situation, the even smaller town of [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], population 8,913, hosts the [[New York Giants]] and [[New York Jets]]; the same city previously hosted the now-[[Brooklyn Nets]], [[New Jersey Devils]] and now-[[New York Red Bulls]]. East Rutherford, although in a different state, is part of the [[New York City metropolitan area]].\n\n==Teams by metropolitan area==\nThe following list contains all metropolitan areas in the United States and Canada containing at least one team in any of the six major leagues. The number of teams in the big four leagues (B4) and the big six leagues (B6), and the city's teams in the National Football League (NFL),<ref name=\"NFL teams\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/teams|title=NFL teams|website=National Football League|accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> Major League Baseball (MLB),<ref name=\"MLB teams\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/index.jsp?tcid=nav_mlb_sitelist|title=Team-by-Team Information|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> the National Basketball Association (NBA),<ref name=\"NBA teams\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/teams/|title=Team Index|publisher=National Basketball Association|accessdate=January 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621040048/https://www.nba.com/teams|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> the National Hockey League (NHL),<ref name=\"NHL teams\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/teams.htm#?nav-tms-main|title=NHL teams|website=National Hockey League|accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> Major League Soccer (MLS),<ref name=\"MLS teams\">{{cite web|title=Clubs|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/clubs|publisher=Major League Soccer|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> and the Canadian Football League (CFL).<ref name=\"CFL teams\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfl.ca/|title=CFL.ca \u2013 Official site of the Canadian Football League|publisher=Canadian Football League|accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref>  No metropolitan area has teams in all six leagues, as NFL teams are exclusively in the United States and CFL teams are exclusively in Canada.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! [[Metropolitan area]]\n! Country\n! Pop.<br>rank\n! Population <br>(2016 est.)<ref name=pop>{{cite web|url=http://www.demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227053418/http://www.demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|archivedate=December 27, 2016|title=Demographia World Urban Areas \u2013 12th Annual Edition|date=April 2016|accessdate=April 25, 2016|publisher=[[Demographia]]}}</ref>\n! B4\n! NFL\n! MLB\n! NBA\n! NHL\n! B6\n! MLS\n! CFL\n|-\n| [[New York metropolitan area|New York City]]\n| United States\n| 1\n| 20,153,634\n| 9\n| {{sort|2|[[New York Giants|Giants]]<br>[[New York Jets|Jets]]}}{{#tag:ref|Seven NFL teams have previously played in the New York City area: the [[New York Brickley Giants|New York Giants]] ([[1921 New York Brickley Giants season|1921]]; no relation to the current Giants), the [[Brooklyn Lions]] (1926), the [[New York Yankees (NFL)|New York Yankees]] (1927-1929), the [[Orange/Newark Tornadoes]] (1929-1930), the [[Staten Island Stapletons]] (1929-1932), the [[Brooklyn Dodgers (NFL)|Brooklyn Dodgers/Tigers/Yanks]] (1930-1945), and the [[New York Yanks|New York Bulldogs/Yanks]] (1949-1951).|group=note}}\n| {{sort|2|[[New York Yankees|Yankees]]<br>[[New York Mets|Mets]]}}{{#tag:ref|The [[New York Mutuals]] played in the [[National League]]'s inaugural season in 1876, but were expelled at the end of that season. The next year, the [[Hartford Dark Blues]] moved to nearby [[Brooklyn]] (then an independent city) and played the 1877 season as the Hartfords before it dissolved. The [[History of the New York Giants (baseball)|Gothams/Giants]] played in [[Manhattan]] from 1883, and the [[History of the Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn Atlantics/Grays/Bridegrooms/Grooms/Bridegrooms/Superbas/Trolley Dodgers/Superbas/Robins/Dodgers]] played in Brooklyn (which became part of New York City in 1898) from 1890 (when it joined the NL from the [[American Association (19th century)|AA]]); both teams respectively moved to [[San Francisco Giants|San Francisco]] and [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Los Angeles]] in 1958.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|2|[[New York Knicks|Knicks]]<br>[[Brooklyn Nets|Nets]]}}\n| {{sort|3|[[New York Rangers|Rangers]]<br>[[New York Islanders|Islanders]]<br>[[New Jersey Devils|Devils]]}}{{#tag:ref|The [[New York Americans|New York/Brooklyn Americans]] played in the NHL from [[1925-26 NHL season|1925]] until suspending operations in [[1941-42 NHL season|1942]], and were disbanded in 1946.|group=note}}\n| 11\n| {{sort|2|[[New York Red Bulls|Red Bulls]]<br>[[New York City FC]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles metropolitan area|Los Angeles]]\n| United States\n| 2\n| 13,310,447\n| 8\n| {{sort|2|[[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]]<br>[[Los Angeles Chargers|Chargers]]}}{{refn|The Rams and Chargers are both in their second stints in the Los Angeles market. The Rams arrived from Cleveland in 1946 and played in the L.A. area until moving to [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis]] after the 1995 season; they would return to L.A. in 2016. The Chargers were originally based in Los Angeles, playing there for the AFL's first season in 1960 before moving to [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego]], where they would play until returning to L.A. in 2017. In addition to the Rams and Chargers, two other NFL teams have called Los Angeles home. The [[Los Angeles Buccaneers|Buccaneers]] played in the 1926 season; despite representing Los Angeles, the team operated out of Chicago because of the difficulty of transcontinental travel in the era before modern air travel. The [[Oakland Raiders]] played in Los Angeles from 1982 to 1994, before they moved back to Oakland.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|2|[[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]]<br>[[Los Angeles Angels|Angels]]}}\n| {{sort|2|[[Los Angeles Lakers|Lakers]]<br>[[Los Angeles Clippers|Clippers]]}}\n| {{sort|2|[[Los Angeles Kings|Kings]]<br>[[Anaheim Ducks|Ducks]]}}\n| 10\n| {{sort|2|[[LA Galaxy|Galaxy]]<br>[[Los Angeles FC]]{{#tag:ref|[[Chivas USA|Club Deportivo Chivas USA]] was a Major League Soccer club that existed between 2005 and 2014 before folding.<ref name=\"LAFC\">{{cite press release|title=MLS announces new strategy for Los Angeles market, 2015 conference alignment|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/10/27/mls-announces-new-strategy-los-angeles-market|publisher=Major League Soccer|date=October 27, 2014|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref>|group=note}}}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago metropolitan area|Chicago]]\n| United States\n| 3\n| 9,512,999\n| 5\n| {{sort|1|[[Chicago Bears|Bears]]}}{{#tag:ref|The [[History of the Chicago Cardinals|Chicago Cardinals]] were a charter franchise of the NFL, before moving to St. Louis in 1960.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|2|[[Chicago Cubs|Cubs]]<br>[[Chicago White Sox|White Sox]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Chicago Bulls|Bulls]]}}{{#tag:ref|Chicago has had two prior NBA teams: the [[Chicago Stags|Stags]] existed from 1946 to 1950 before folding, and the [[Chicago Packers|Packers]]/[[Chicago Zephyrs|Zephyrs]] played from 1961 to 1963, before moving to Baltimore.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Chicago Blackhawks|Blackhawks]]}}\n| 6\n| {{sort|1|[[Chicago Fire FC|Fire]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[San Francisco Bay Area]]\n| United States\n| 6\n| 6,657,982\n| 5\n| {{sort|1|[[San Francisco 49ers|49ers]]}}{{#tag:ref|The [[History of the Oakland Raiders|Oakland Raiders]] called Oakland home from 1960 until 1982 and again from 1995 until 2019 before [[Oakland Raiders relocation to Las Vegas|relocating to Las Vegas]] becoming the [[Las Vegas Raiders]].|group=note}}\n| {{sort|2|[[San Francisco Giants|Giants]]<br>[[Oakland Athletics|Athletics]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Golden State Warriors|Warriors]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[San Jose Sharks|Sharks]]}}{{#tag:ref|The [[California Golden Seals]] were an NHL expansion team which played in Oakland from [[1967\u201368 NHL season|1967]]\u2013[[1975\u201376 NHL season|76]], when they moved to [[Cleveland]] to become the [[Cleveland Barons (NHL)|Cleveland Barons]].|group=note}}\n| 6\n| {{sort|1|[[San Jose Earthquakes|Earthquakes]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]]\n| United States\n| 4\n| 7,233,323\n| 4\n| {{sort|1|[[Dallas Cowboys|Cowboys]]}}\n| {{sort|1