ng play in 2002 as the New Orleans Hornets, then renaming themselves as the Pelicans in 2013.|group=note}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| 2\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Buffalo\u2013Niagara Falls metropolitan area|Buffalo]]\n| United States\n| 47\n| 1,132,804\n| 2\n| {{sort|1|[[Buffalo Bills|Bills]]}}{{refn|Before the Bills joined the NFL as a result of the [[AFL-NFL merger]] in 1970, two other NFL teams played in the Buffalo area. The [[Buffalo (NFL)|All-Americans/Bisons/Rangers/Bisons]] played in the city under several different owners until 1929 (not playing the 1928 season), while the [[Tonawanda Kardex Lumbermen]] played in [[Tonawanda (city), New York|Tonawanda]] in the 1921 season, but disbanded after a lopsided loss in their sole NFL game. From the 2008 to 2013 seasons, the Bills hosted one of their regular season games and a number of preseason games at Toronto's [[Rogers Centre]] as part of the [[Bills Toronto Series]].|group=note}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|{{refn|The [[Buffalo Bisons (NL)|Bisons]] played in the [[National League]] from 1879 until it left the league in 1885; the [[Buffalo Bisons|Bisons]] have played in the minor leagues in one form or another since.|group=note}}}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|{{refn|The [[Buffalo Braves]] were an NBA team that moved to [[San Diego]], [[California]] in 1978 to become the [[San Diego Clippers]].|group=note}}}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Buffalo Sabres|Sabres]]}}\n| 2\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Greater Montreal|Montreal]]\n| Canada\n| 15\n| 4,098,927\n| 1\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|{{refn|Montreal was home to a Major League Baseball team, the [[Montreal Expos]], beginning in [[1969 Montreal Expos season|1969]]. However, the team moved to Washington, D.C. in [[2005 Washington Nationals season|2005]], where it was renamed as the [[Washington Nationals]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bloom|first=Barry M.|title=MLB selects D.C. for Expos|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/content/printer_friendly/mlb/y2004/m09/d29/c875100.jsp|work=[[MLB.com]]|date=September 29, 2004|accessdate=September 29, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1946925&type=story|work=ESPN.com|title=Ballpark financing issue may kill deal|date=December 15, 2004|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1890915&type=story|work=ESPN.com|title=Announcement will come Wednesday|date=September 28, 2004|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>|group=note}}}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Montreal Canadiens|Canadiens]]}}\n| 3\n| {{sort|1|[[Montreal Impact|Impact]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Montreal Alouettes|Alouettes]]}}\n|-\n| [[Greater Vancouver|Vancouver]]\n| Canada\n| 24\n| 2,463,431\n| 1\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|{{refn|The expansion [[Vancouver Grizzlies]] of the NBA began play in 1995. However, in 2001 the team [[Vancouver Grizzlies relocation to Memphis|moved]] to [[Memphis, Tennessee]] and was renamed as the [[Memphis Grizzlies]].|group=note}}}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Vancouver Canucks|Canucks]]}}\n| 3\n| {{sort|1|[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC|Whitecaps FC]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[BC Lions|Lions]]}}\n|-\n| [[Greater Orlando|Orlando]]\n| United States\n| 25\n| 2,441,257\n| 1\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Orlando Magic|Magic]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| 2\n| {{sort|1| [[Orlando City SC]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Portland metropolitan area|Portland]]\n| United States\n| 27\n| 2,424,955\n| 1\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Portland Trail Blazers|Trail Blazers]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| 2\n| {{sort|1|[[Portland Timbers|Timbers]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Columbus, Ohio metropolitan area|Columbus]]\n| United States\n| 34\n| 2,041,520\n| 1\n